  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>St James Sqre Weddy Morg 10 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest Mate. I must say that my dear London looks as horrible &amp; as glum as it is possible to do, this morning; with a yellow fog. I could barely see to eat my breakfast at 9 o'clock. I dare say it is fine &amp; delightful a little way in the country. My ride</p>
      <p>yesterday was as agreeable as a solitary ride could be. The aspect of everything &amp; the feel fo the air, were delicious. I am glad we got here without accident to James or the filly. She was very troublesome. London will do her good.--</p>
      <p>I had a Singing-Lesson yesterday after my arrival here; &amp; after my dinner went to Madselle Bertucat's for an hour. I then returned, to receive</p>
      <p>Dr Locock, who staid till rather late; &amp; we were very merry &amp; chatty.--</p>
      <p>I have as yet seen no one else.</p>
      <p>I did not go to any Theatre last night; partly from real non-inclination; but also in consequence of expecting Dr L--.</p>
      <p>Tonight I may possibly go to the French Play. But this will depend on the time of Hester's arrival, &amp; on whether she is inclined to go with me. For I do not wish</p>
      <p>to neglect her the first evening.-- So you see I am not quite Theatrical- -mad this year.--</p>
      <p>I think there has been some rain in the night; for I see the roofs look only half-dry.</p>
      <p>At Esher yesterday I hear that Mrs Edward Noel has had a son; &amp; that her Accouchement was extraordinarily easy &amp; rapid.</p>
      <p>They had wished for a boy this time too.</p>
      <p>E. L seems to me fading away more &amp; more. Alas her death would half-kill the Hen.</p>
    </div></body>
